<font color="#FF0000">TO JOHN</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jun 28  7:25:07 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
John,<br><br>
I was pulling guard duty in our battalion's sector of perimeter on LZ Bayonet. In Vietnam there was a 6 o'clock curfew for civilians.<br><br>
At five minutes after six a couple of Vietnamese farmers were herding their cattle home in the distance. All of a sudden the bunker next to mine opened fire on them with their M16's. In horror, I watched as little puffs were raised in the dirt in front of them. I screamed at them to cease fire. They continued to shoot as the farmers frantically jumped up and down - trying to get their cattle to hurry.<br><br>
In a few minutes they made their way over to the other side of a small hill and continued on their way home.<br><br>
That sight will forever play in my mind. It is something I will never ever forget. It is also the type of action that was protested back in America by people who came to be known as &quot;communist sympathizers&quot;.<br><br>
I thought I answered your questions, in that I provided evidence that the VC did not need to have guns held to their heads. That evidence is the sheer number of VC who died for their cause. I didn't answer your questions about the Vietnamese villagers, because I was reluctant to tell the above story - which undoubtedly is painful for Americans to read. <br><br>
No doubt they were perpetrated by a distinct minority of Americans, but the bad apples spoiled the barrel in that we were perceived by many Vietnamese as being no better than the VC. Don't think for one millisecond that this was the only incident of this sort that I witnessed.<br><br>
I am not going to ask you what you would have done if you had been one of those farmers. But, I know what I would have done if someone indescriminately fired at me or members of my family who were unarmed. I wouldn't need anyone to encourage me by holding a gun to my head, either. <br><br>
I didn't need to ask the villagers anything because I knew the reasons for their fear and distrust of us. <br><br>
Put yourself in their shoes regarding the treaty in Geneva, and the resultant *appointment* of Diem as President. A Catholic who had no regard for the Buddhists in the countryside, and who failed to deal with the land reform issue.<br><br>
The thought of Ho Chi Minh being president of north and south Vietnam - had the Geneva treaty been adhered to - is not a rosy scenario. But that result would have been preferable to the misery that the war brought to the Vietnamese people, in my opinion. Do we need reminding that the country is still reeling from the turmoil and devastation?<br><br>
An invasion of the north by American and ARVN forces would have succeeded in furthering the destruction and would have necessitated a greater presence (and loss) of American troops. That is unless we followed Curtis Lemay's advice and bombed them back to the stone age. <br><br>
What would they or we have been left with then? <br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


